Great! If Jordan prefers `snake_case` for database columns, you can adjust your database schema and your API code accordingly. Here’s how you can implement `snake_case` conventions in your PostgreSQL database and ensure that your Fastify API aligns with that style.

### Database Schema

When creating your database tables, use `snake_case` for column names. Here’s an example SQL statement to create a table with `snake_case` column names:

```sql
CREATE TABLE items (
    id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    description TEXT
);
```

### Adjusting the API Code

When you interact with the database in your Fastify API, make sure to use `snake_case` for the column names in your queries. Here’s how you can adjust the example routes to reflect this:

#### Example Route with `snake_case`

In `src/routes/example.ts`, modify the queries to use `snake_case`:

```typescript
import { FastifyPluginAsync } from 'fastify';
import { query } from '../database';

const exampleRoutes: FastifyPluginAsync = async (fastify) => {
  // Get all items
  fastify.get('/api/items', async (request, reply) => {
    const result = await query('SELECT * FROM items');
    return result.rows;
  });

  // Create a new item
  fastify.post('/api/items', async (request, reply) => {
    const { name, description } = request.body; // Assuming request body uses camelCase
    const result = await query(
      'INSERT INTO items(name, description) VALUES($1, $2) RETURNING *',
      [name, description]
    );
    reply.code(201).send(result.rows[0]);
  });
};

export default exampleRoutes;
```

### Handling Request and Response

If you want to maintain a consistent API style, you might want to convert between `camelCase` (for the API) and `snake_case` (for the database). You can create utility functions to handle this conversion.

#### Utility Functions for Conversion

You can create a utility file, e.g., `src/utils/caseConverter.ts`, to handle the conversion:

```typescript
// src/utils/caseConverter.ts

export const toSnakeCase = (obj: Record<string, any>): Record<string, any> => {
  return Object.fromEntries(
    Object.entries(obj).map(([key, value]) => [key.replace(/([A-Z])/g, '_$1').toLowerCase(), value])
  );
};

export const toCamelCase = (obj: Record<string, any>): Record<string, any> => {
  return Object.fromEntries(
    Object.entries(obj).map(([key, value]) => [
      key.replace(/(_\w)/g, (m) => m[1].toUpperCase()),
      value,
    ])
  );
};
```

#### Using the Utility Functions

You can use these utility functions in your routes to convert between `snake_case` and `camelCase`:

```typescript
import { FastifyPluginAsync } from 'fastify';
import { query } from '../database';
import { toSnakeCase, toCamelCase } from '../utils/caseConverter';

const exampleRoutes: FastifyPluginAsync = async (fastify) => {
  // Get all items
  fastify.get('/api/items', async (request, reply) => {
    const result = await query('SELECT * FROM items');
    return result.rows.map(toCamelCase); // Convert to camelCase for response
  });

  // Create a new item
  fastify.post('/api/items', async (request, reply) => {
    const snakeCaseBody = toSnakeCase(request.body); // Convert to snake_case for DB
    const result = await query(
      'INSERT INTO items(name, description) VALUES($1, $2) RETURNING *',
      [snakeCaseBody.name, snakeCaseBody.description]
    );
    reply.code(201).send(toCamelCase(result.rows[0])); // Convert to camelCase for response
  });
};

export default exampleRoutes;
```

### Conclusion

By following these conventions, you can ensure that your API remains consistent with Jordan's preference for `snake_case` in the database while still providing a user-friendly `camelCase` interface for API consumers. This approach helps maintain clarity and consistency throughout your application. If you have any further questions or need additional features, feel free to ask!

